04216nam a22005895i 9780300145199DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20082008ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001451997 a10.12987/97803001451992doi  a(DE-B1597)485002  a(OCoLC)666930730  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aD16.2b.L44 2008 7aBIO0190002bisacsh04a907.1/174472221 aLefkowitz, Mary, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHistory Lesson :bA Race Odyssey /cMary Lefkowitz. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tINTRODUCTION -- tCHAPTER ONE .A Racist Incident? -- tCHAPTER TWO . Discovering Afrocentrism -- tCHAPTER THREE . Two Views of Ancient History -- tCHAPTER FOUR . Turning Myths into History -- tCHAPTER FIVE . A New Anti-Semitism -- tCHAPTER SIX. Truth or Slander? -- tCHAPTER SEVEN . Reparations? -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. A Racist Polemic? -- tCHAPTER NINE. Turning History into Fiction -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the early 1990s, Classics professor Mary Lefkowitz discovered that one of her faculty colleagues at Wellesley College was teaching his students that Greek culture had been stolen from Africa and that Jews were responsible for the slave trade. This book tells the disturbing story of what happened when she spoke out. Lefkowitz quickly learned that to investigate the origin and meaning of myths composed by people who have for centuries been dead and buried is one thing, but it is quite another to critique myths that living people take very seriously. She also found that many in academia were reluctant to challenge the fashionable idea that truth is merely a form of opinion. For her insistent defense of obvious truths about the Greeks and the Jews, Lefkowitz was embroiled in turmoil for a decade. She faced institutional indifference, angry colleagues, reverse racism, anti-Semitism, and even a lawsuit intended to silence her. In History Lesson Lefkowitz describes what it was like to experience directly the power of both postmodernism and compensatory politics. She offers personal insights into important issues of academic values and political correctness, and she suggests practical solutions for the divisive and painful problems that arise when a political agenda takes precedence over objective scholarship. Her forthright tale uncovers surprising features in the landscape of higher education and an unexpected need for courage from those who venture there.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAcademic freedom. 0aAntisemitism in higher education. 0aHistoryxStudy and teaching (Higher)zMassachusetts. 0aPostmodernism and higher education. 0aRacism in higher education. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Educators.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030012659440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030014519940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300145199423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300145199/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY